&lt;body&gt;
&lt;p class=&quot;defaultstyle&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot; font-size: 13.5pt; font-family: &apos;Gentium Plus&apos;;&quot;&gt;Elimelech Basch was a member of the Jewish community of Tyachiv in eastern Hungary (today western Ukraine), invaded by the Nazis in March 1944. Between the years 1942-1944 Basch kept a diary, written in fine Hebrew&lt;/span&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;span style=&quot; font-size: 13.5pt;&quot;&gt;, &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;span style=&quot; font-size: 13.5pt; font-family: &apos;Gentium Plus&apos;;&quot;&gt;which describes the situation of the Jewish community there. During this period the Jews suffered from the oppressive Hungarian and Nazi regimes and moved between despair and hope.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p class=&quot;defaultstyle&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot; font-size: 13.5pt; font-family: &apos;Gentium Plus&apos;;&quot;&gt;During the Jewish festival of Shavuot, May 1944, the Jews of Tyachiv were all deported to Auschwitz.&amp;#160; Of the Basch family - parents and their eight children &#8211; only one survived.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p class=&quot;defaultstyle&quot;&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p class=&quot;defaultstyle&quot; style=&quot; margin: 0cm; margin-bottom: .0001pt; text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;span style=&quot; font-size: 13.5pt;&quot;&gt;Photo&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;span style=&quot; font-size: 13.5pt;&quot;&gt;: The Basch family at the beginning of the 1930&apos;s. &amp;#160;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot; font-size: 13.5pt; line-height: 115%; font-family: Calibri,sans-serif;&quot;&gt;Highlighted is the only surviving member of the family, Mrs. Perhiya Senderovich (formerly Bluma Blanka Basch), who now lives in Israel.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/body&gt;
&lt;/html&gt;

&lt;!DOCTYPE html PUBLIC &quot;-//W3C//DTD XHTML 1.0 Transitional//EN&quot; &quot;http://www.w3.org/TR/xhtml1/DTD/xhtml1-transitional.dtd&quot;&gt; 
