--&gt;
&lt;/style&gt;
&lt;/head&gt;
&lt;body&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Maimonides was greatly influenced by Muslim philosophers who combined Aristotelian and Neoplatonic philosophy, such as Farabi, Ibn Sina&amp;#160; (Avicenna),&amp;#160; and the Spanish Ibn Bajja (Avempace) (Zaragoza 1095-1138). Maimonides&#8217; writings influenced the great Christian scholastic theologians such as Aquinas and Albertus Magnus, &amp;#160;and, in later centuries , Spinoza and Leibnitz.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/body&gt;
&lt;/html&gt;

&lt;!DOCTYPE html PUBLIC &quot;-//W3C//DTD XHTML 1.0 Transitional//EN&quot; &quot;http://www.w3.org/TR/xhtml1/DTD/xhtml1-transitional.dtd&quot;&gt; 
&lt;html xmlns=&quot;http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml&quot;&gt;
&lt;head&gt;
&lt;meta name=&quot;generator&quot; content=&quot;EditLive! 7.6.2.10&quot; /&gt;
&lt;meta name=&quot;generator&quot; content=&quot;TheBrain 7.0.4.5&quot; /&gt;
