&lt;body&gt;
&lt;p class=&quot;DefaultStyle&quot; align=&quot;left&quot; style=&quot; margin-left: 32.2pt; text-align: left;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot; background: white;&quot;&gt;Following this composition, Maimonides wrote his most famous treatise called the &lt;i&gt;Mishneh Torah&lt;/i&gt;, a comprehensive code of Jewish Law which is conceived throughout the Jewish world as &lt;span style=&quot; color: black;&quot;&gt;one of the chief authoritative codifications of Jewish law and ethics, as well as other important writings. In this great composition Maimonides broke from&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt; one thousand years of legal precedent of writing commentaries to produce a systematic codification of Jewish law by subject. Although most of Maimonides&#8217; treatises were written in Judeo-Arabic, Maimonides composed the Code in Hebrew&lt;span style=&quot; color: red;&quot;&gt; &lt;/span&gt;to ensure its accessibility for Jews all over the world.&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p class=&quot;DefaultStyle&quot; align=&quot;left&quot; dir=&quot;LTR&quot; style=&quot; margin-left: 32.2pt; text-align: left;&quot;&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/body&gt;
&lt;/html&gt;

&lt;!DOCTYPE html PUBLIC &quot;-//W3C//DTD XHTML 1.0 Transitional//EN&quot; &quot;http://www.w3.org/TR/xhtml1/DTD/xhtml1-transitional.dtd&quot;&gt;&lt;html xmlns=&quot;http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml&quot;&gt;
&lt;head&gt;
&lt;meta name=&quot;generator&quot; content=&quot;EditLive! 7.6.2.10&quot; /&gt;
