&lt;/head&gt;
&lt;body&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The Guide of the Perplexed, an important philosophical treatise, which was composed between 1185-1191, is set as a letter to a young disciple. The Guide sought to resolve apparent contradictions between rationalist philosophy on the one hand, and Jewish tradition found in Scripture and the Talmud, on the other hand.&amp;#160; Unlike the &lt;i&gt;Mishneh Torah&lt;/i&gt;, which was written for broad use, the &lt;i&gt;Guide&lt;/i&gt;, written in Judeo-Arabic,&amp;#160; was written for a more limited audience of rationalist yet traditional Jews. A few of Maimonides&#8217; theological positions led to public controversies with rabbinic leaders&amp;#160; outside of Egypt towards the end of his life.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/body&gt;
&lt;/html&gt;

&lt;!DOCTYPE html PUBLIC &quot;-//W3C//DTD XHTML 1.0 Transitional//EN&quot; &quot;http://www.w3.org/TR/xhtml1/DTD/xhtml1-transitional.dtd&quot;&gt;&lt;html xmlns=&quot;http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml&quot;&gt;
&lt;head&gt;
&lt;meta name=&quot;generator&quot; content=&quot;EditLive! 7.6.2.10&quot; /&gt;
&lt;meta name=&quot;generator&quot; content=&quot;TheBrain 7.0.4.5&quot; /&gt;
&lt;meta http-equiv=&quot;Content-Type&quot; content=&quot;text/html; charset=UTF-8&quot; /&gt;
&lt;style type=&quot;text/css&quot;&gt;
&lt;!--
