&lt;/style&gt;
&lt;/head&gt;
&lt;body&gt;
&lt;p class=&quot;DefaultStyle&quot; style=&quot; margin-left: 36.0pt; text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;In 1872, one of Newton&apos;s descendants, the 5th Earl of Portsmouth, donated the papers to the University of Cambridge, in which Newton had studied and taught. The committee appointed by the University to review the papers, selected only Newton&apos;s scientific papers, not wanting to blemish his reputation as an enlightened intellectual and scientist.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p class=&quot;DefaultStyle&quot; style=&quot; margin-left: 36.0pt; text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;The theological papers, as well as the alchemical and the historical papers were returned to the family.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/body&gt;
&lt;/html&gt;

&lt;!DOCTYPE html PUBLIC &quot;-//W3C//DTD XHTML 1.0 Transitional//EN&quot; &quot;http://www.w3.org/TR/xhtml1/DTD/xhtml1-transitional.dtd&quot;&gt;&lt;html xmlns=&quot;http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml&quot;&gt;
&lt;head&gt;
&lt;meta name=&quot;generator&quot; content=&quot;EditLive! 7.6.2.10&quot; /&gt;
&lt;meta name=&quot;generator&quot; content=&quot;TheBrain 7.0.4.5&quot; /&gt;
&lt;meta http-equiv=&quot;Content-Type&quot; content=&quot;text/html; charset=UTF-8&quot; /&gt;
&lt;style type=&quot;text/css&quot;&gt;
&lt;!--
